==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|la}} {{term|meticulosus||full of fear}} < {{term|metus||fear}}

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-uk-meticulous.ogg|Audio (UK)}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# With [[extreme]] [[care]], [[precision]], and [[attention]] to [[detail]].
#* {{quote-book|year=1943|author=Franklin Roosevelt|title=[[S:Roosevelt's Fireside Chat, 28 July 1943|Roosevelt's Fireside Chat, 28 July 1943]]
|passage=The '''meticulous''' care with which the operation in Sicily was planned has paid dividends. Our casualties in men, in ships and materiel have been low—in fact, far below our estimate.}}
{{rfc|The definition should be rephrased: the current definition "with extreme care..." is of an adverb, not of an adjective.}}

====Usage notes====
* It may be used in praise, synonymous with [[painstaking]]; or pejoratively, for [[absorption]] to [[neglect]] of [[constraint]]s in [[time]] and [[resources]].

====Synonyms====
* [[careful]], [[precise]], [[painstaking]], [[rigorous]], [[scrupulous]]
* See also [[Wikisaurus:meticulous]]

====Antonyms====
* [[sloppy]], [[careless]], [[slapdash]]

